{"/service/ndnp/nmu/batch_nmu_barberry_ver04/data/sn93061777/00280774479/1913072401/0410.xml":{"full_text":"The Clovis News\nThe News Printing Company\n(Ir\nJ. E. Curren. Editor.\nArthur E. Curren, Manager.\nEntered at the post office at\nClovis, N. M. as second class\nmatter under the act of March\n3, 1879.\nTERMS OF SUBSCRIPTION\nOne Year $1.00\nSix Months 50\nThe folly of harboring a \"red\nlight\" district in the heart of\nthe city, within a block of the\nmain business thoroughfare and\npracticelly adjoining the freight\ndepot is just now being brought\nto the attention of the Clovis\npeople by evangelist Rev. T. 0.\nReese, who with his singer J.\nP. Scholfield ae couducting\nnightly revival meetings at the\nBaptist church.\nMr. Reese is handling the sit\nuation \"without gloves\" as the\nsaying is and his criticism of\nthis public nuisance is timely\nand correct.\nIf the bawdy house is a nec\nessary evil then why not locate\nit in some remote section or se\ncluded spot on the outskirts of\nthe city and not where the fam\nilies of respectable residents\ncan see them daily. It is said\nthat the denizens of the district\nare becoming so soliticious as to\ngive the hailing sign\" to pas\nsengers on the trains. fJgH\nAlderman Childers said tftt\nhe was in favor of their remov\nal if a suitable location could be\nselected without incurring new\nopposition.\nAlderman Townsen thought\nthey could be best governed if\nlocated right on main street un\nder the constant watch of the\nofficers.\nThe News is informed that\nthe railroad officials are very\nmuch displeased with the pres\nent location of the district and\nare lending encouragement to\nthe thought of its removal.\nWhatever may be said or done\nthe fact remains that public\nsentiment is against the policy\nof maintaining a \"red light\"\ndistrict in the heart of the city.\nthickening stream.\nWe have learned to irrigate\nand drain, to select seed, to\nutilize farm by-products, to em\nploy hired-men with real\nsteam behind them. Science\nis battling successfully with\nthe scales and weevils that once\ndestroyed yields of whole states.\nCompetent veterinaay super\nvision has begun to stamp out\n-i i i i\nI i-..,ue;B milium uur iirirus BtlU\nflocks.\nAmerica was never so basi\ncally sound and never enjoyed\na more healthy constitution.\nDuring the past year more\nmoney has been paid out in\nwages than ever before. Store\nrooms are filled, and purses are\nfilled. There are goods to be\nsold and purchasers to bay.\nNever before has the buying\npublic of America been so well\nable to afford the things they\nwant, and never before has\nthere been so much tourchase.\nOpportunity is smiling as\nnever before uprn the American\nmerchant, demanding that he\nprepare to handle a good year's\ngreat business.\nf\nI\nSeveral Democrats of Las Ve\ngas, Clayton and Clovis are\nstruggling hard to build up and\nmaintain progressive Democrat\nic papers, but the carpet-baggers\nin their own party have succeed\ned in getting hold of the \"offices\nand the party machine\" with the\nresult that many of the old vet\nerans and their papers some of\nthem the oldest and most loyal\nin the State are being heartless\nly crushed out of business. Of\ncourse, if it was a contest case\nor a case of rivalry between op\nposition party papers and the\nveteran democratic editors\nout, then in that event, the\nrns would take their loss\nwith a good grace but having\nfought the battles of the demo\ncratic party every day for a quar\nter of a centuary in New Mexico\nand then at the end of victory to\nbe horn-swoggled out of the just\nearned \"spoils (the federal pat\nronage) is enough to drive a\nwhite man into the lunatic asy\nlum or the socialist party. Poli\ntics, (or rather politicians) are\ngetting to be the most heartless\nset of ingfates in the world.\nvete\nThe Business Outlook.\nThere never was more money\nin America never was more\nprosperity never so many\nacres under cultivation never\nsuch a heavy yield per acre\nnever more factories in opera\ntionnever better prices and\nbigger profits on products and\nproduce.\nWe are selling more goods to\nmore foreign countries. Pro\nportionate to increase in popu\nlation, our imports are constant\nly shrinking and our exports\nare attaining fuller volume.\nWe are steel makers for the\nuniverse wheat raisers for the\nfive races- machinery builders\nlocomotive constructorc and\nbridge erectors for every kind\non earth. We are not only\nholding our own as sellers, but\neach month we lessen our\npurchases abroad.\nCan't you see the trend of\nthese tremendous times? The\nbalance of trade is colossal ly in\nm v y\nour iavor. xnoc only are we\nkeeping our money at home but\nfrancs and kreutzers and guin\nOur banixMB\nis a national sank\nlet us take care ofjj\nYOUR MONEY v-ljiW\nThe Republican Registers of\nthe Clayton, Ft. Sumner and\nother land offices are holding\nonto their jobs like a puppy dog\nto a root and what makes it\nlook so bad is the fact that they\nare uuing the democratic party\nmachine\" to retain their hold\non the office. The public don't\nblame the republicans for hold\ning on as long as they can, but\nthey do blame the grafting dem\nocrat who is quietly standing-in\nwith the republican register for\nthe patronage of his office.\nCrane's Second Hand Stores\nhave been moved this week into\nthe Owen building adjoining\nSteed's Undertaking parlors on\nwest urana Avenue. mr.\nCrane will discontinue the store\non central Main St. also the one\non east Grand Avenue and con\nsolidate both in the new location.\nHis reasons for moving, he\nsays, is in orde.' lo obtain lower\ninsurance rates.\nA traction.\nAt the Lyceum Theatre the\nhouse of amusement. Running\nsix reels of pictures each night\nat the same old price of 10 and\n15c.\nWe show comedy and funny\npictures as well as educational\nand instructive ones.\nWe have good music every\nnight. We change program\neach night.\nC. C, Calucott, Mngr.\nYour money will be safe in our\nNational Bank, which has a charter\nfrom the U. S Government to do a\nBanking business. Under our charter\nwe must conduct our business under\nthe National Banking Act. This law\nplaces our bank under the supervision\nof the Treasury Department at Wash\nington. A RIGID EXAMINATION\nof the bank's affairs is made several\ntimes every year in the interest of its\ndepositors.\n\"Make OUR Bank YOUR Bank\"\nFirst National Bank\nof Clovis\nCapital and Surplus $42,000.00\nThe success of your town\nmeans your success. JJc loyai\nto it and its institutions as you\nare to your personal interests.\nGive your home town and its\nvarious enterprises your loyal\nsupport and it will be returned\nto you again. -jr-Fort Sumner\nReview.\nMiss Ethel Chambers, of To\npeka, Kansas is in the city for\nthe purpose of establishing a\nlibrary in our city.\nDr. E. M. Chapman and\nwife returned Monday from an\nextended visit in Kansas City\nand an outing in the Ozarks.\nGrand Lodge Order of\nMoose.\nFor the above accasion, tick-\nets will be on sale, Clovis to\nCincinati, O., and return July\n24. 25. 26, 27, 28th at rate of\n$47.00 for the t round trip.\nGood to return 'until Aucrust\n16th 1913.\nD. C. Knowles, Agt.\n\"The Quality Tells and the Price\nSells\" That is the secret of\nour success in selling\nGROCERIES\nAccording to a press report\nfrom Santa Fe, corporation pa\npers have been granted to an\nassociation to be known as\n\"The Co-operative Association\nof Tucumcaai.\" Among the in\ncorporators are many promi\nnent Socialists of Quay county,\nand the object is to pool the in\nterests of the socialists of the\ncounty, for trading them stock\nin the company for their land\nand improuements, etc.\nThe future or this idea of\ngovernment will be watched\nwith considerable interest, from\nthe fact that all similar experi\nments have been failures.\nSpace will not permit us to\nenumerate the many table\nnecessities and quote our\nlow prices, but you will be\nsatisfied if you trade with\nHARVEY MORRIS\n\"The Leading Grocers\"\nIn the Heart of the Business District. Phone 25\ni\nO\neas and liras and marks are\nHouse News.","height":"24772","width":"16580"}}
